Continuing to lift this family that is still separated. The state has taken both children. @syesha and Tyron’s newborn daughter was only 10 days old when they ripped her away from her mother’s arms to take her into custody. This past weekend CPS did not arrange for pick up of Syesha’s milk, so not only are they separated, she’s not able to ensure her baby is getting breastmilk. They still do not know who is caring for their infant. This is maddening. Bring their babies home!!!! 🙏🏽
_
#repost @syesha
・・・
My Soul Cries for You every second Ra Ra. You belong in our arms. 

You belong with us. Mission. Purpose. Vision. Clear. 

We are always connected no matter the distance. You are always with us my precious baby. 

Mama and Baba Love You. 

If you are new to this page our Sun was “Legally Kidnapped”. It’s been 114 days without Our SUNshine. 

Our sun was unrightfully taken from us due to a false medical report by Child Abuse Pediatrician, Sally Smith who works at Johns Hopkins All Children’s Hospital, in St.Petersburg, FL and CPI Officer Danielle McCoy of Manatee County Sheriff’s Department. 

They claim we refused a medically necessary B12 shot for our sun, which we didn’t. They banned us permanently from the hospital forcing us to leave our sun alone with strangers and then placed him in a foster home with a white family, bypassing all of our qualified relatives. 

Ra had just weaned from my breast while at the hospital and had never been without his mama and baba. EVER. The trauma that they have caused can never be undone. The trauma from all the nights Ra lay in that hospital crib crying out for his mama can NEVER be reversed. 

Ra is our entire world and now everyday we have to relive the beyond heart ache of how they tore our beautiful family apart. They have caused unnecessary trauma to our child… our family and Must be held accountable! 

Please click the link in our bio to Read our Story, watch our highlights and IGTV for more info. and Donate to our #BringRaHome Campaign. 

We appreciate your support in standing with us as we use our voices to bring justice for our Sun, our family, and other families torn apart to such a corrupt and broken system.

I’ve been offline for a few weeks, processing some immense losses in my life and preparing for my son to head to college. I could not stay away after learning about these beautiful babies who have been kidnapped from their family, by the state. @syesha is fighting for her babies. Most recently her newborn was taken forcibly and both children are in state custody. They come from a loving family. They need to be with their mother and father. This is terrorism, it’s abusive and CPS, CPI Danielle McCoy of MCSO, Sally Smith, The Safe Children Coalition of Manatee County and Johns Hopkins All Children’s Hospital - all need to be held accountable. 

This family separation tactic has done irreparable  emotional damage to the parents and will leave lasting emotional harm on the children. They need our help. 

Tune into @syesha’s page to learn more, donate to their legal fund, share far and wide. 

#repost @syesha
・・・
This was us. Living a simple and natural lifestyle, filled with lots of SUNshine and Nature.

CPS, CPI Danielle McCoy of MCSO, MD Sally Smith, The Safe Children Coalition of Manatee County, Johns Hopkins All Children’s Hospital turned our world upside down and introduced to our family terror and trauma….. damage that can never be undone.

They stole our baby from us. Call it Medical Kidnapping, Legalized Kidnapping, but it was done and this major injustice is not just against MY family, but families all over. Some are suffering in silence. But we will NOT be silenced by this act of terror and injustice.

We are stronger, wiser, and more resilient because of it. It has pushed us into our MISSION to help others not become Victims to this corrupt system. 

We must protect our starseeds.

Visit the Link in our Bio to see how you can help us #BringRaHome

We are powerful in Numbers. 

Please share the posts that resonate with you. We appreciate the continued love and support.

✨GLOWING LIVE WITH LATHAM ✨ IG LIVE series on @iamwellandgood 
_
Hey family! New guest alert 🚨For my interview series in partnership with WELL+GOOD. I interview incredible BIPOC healers and entrepreneurs who are forging a path of service in their communities. TODAY, July 22, as we head into Olympic season, I will be going live with @sanyarichiross - Olympic gold medalist (track and field), mama and founder of the @mommination community. She is also the host of the @nikewomen new visual podcast series, ULTRA SOUND - Conversations for Black Birthing People. 
_
Sanya Richards-Ross is a Jamaican-American former track and field athlete who competed internationally for the United States. At the 2012 Summer Olympics, she won gold in the 400 metres after finishing third at the 2008 Summer Olympics. Richards-Ross has also won Olympic gold in the 4×400 meters relay at the 2004 Summer Olympics, the 2008 Summer Olympics, and the 2012 Summer Olympics. She was the best 400m runner in the world for a decade, ranking No. 1 in the world from 2005-2009 and again in 2012. 
_
We know that there is so much wisdom within our communities and I can’t wait for you to hear from Sanya and some of the other amazing wellness leaders and personalities we have lined up. 
_
Join @glowmaven, doula, wellness maven, and author of Own Your Glow, as she speaks with luminaries from across the wellness industry who are working to create change and promote healing for their communities. These soulful live discussions will give you a peek into their personal self-care routines and rituals while also shining a light on the health disparities that prevent many people from living their most well and fully expressed lives. 
_
See you at 1pm ET today on @iamwellandgood ! #glowinglivewithlatham #iamwellandgood

node.text:
Meet @karmatudor, mother, certified @mamaglow Doula and doula mentor. 
3 years ago Ebonie began her journey with Mama Glow. She came to doula work to heal after her own birth experience. 

Ebonie is one of our incredible birth workers who is guiding families and mentoring other birth workers as part of the ‘LOVE DELIVERED’ initiative with @carolsdaughter and the Mama Glow Foundation @mamaglowfoundation

We are honored that Ebonie was among the folks in our community who shared their stories about birthing while Black for the Mama Glow Foundation initiative in partnership with Carol’s Daughter, ‘Love Delivered’. 

Through ‘Love Delivered’, the Mama Glow Foundation and Carol’s Daughter are raising awareness about Black Maternal Health and ensuring  expectant parents receive the love and support and advocacy tools they need to have a healthy pregnancy, birth and thrive postpartum. 

Become an advocate, donate, learn more at mamaglowfoundation.org/love-delivered

Visit MamaGlow.com to learn more about our doula programs! 

#mamaglow #mamaglowfoundation #doula #blackmaternalhealth #pregnancy #postpartum

Bless our elders, our wisdom keepers. Those who carry our stories in their hearts. Imagine enduring a massacre a century ago... and surviving it. Imagine leaving your home in an instant and witnessing violence unleashed onto your people. And imagine living a hundred years later to testify, and speak your truth. God bless Ms Viola Fletcher. 

The Tulsa massacre is not the first or the only example of white supremacist terrorism that led to genocide and complete destruction of thriving Black communities. We have dozens of instances where land was usurped, homes and businesses were burned down, Black people were tortured, killed and run out of town. Let us not forget the East St. Louis Massacre of 1917 and in 1923, when the all-Black town of Rosewood, Florida was destroyed by an angry white mob. Black people were massacred in at least 26 cities, including Washington, D.C.; Chicago, Illinois; Omaha, Nebraska; Elaine, Arkansas; Charleston, South Carolina; Columbia, Tennessee; Houston, Texas; and Tulsa, Oklahoma. There were 97 lynchings across the country in 1919 alone. Black people were prosperous in so many of these places, we had thriving communities and businesses and in some cases were sitting on valuable land. They endured horrendous violence, displacement and were never able to rebuild in the same way. 🙏🏽 #tulsa #tulsamassacre

node.text:
Food Justice, Food Security, Ancestral Tradition, Ancestral Foods, Seed and Land. Homeland, housing security. Liberation is deeply connected to our ability to move freely and be anchored to the land we call home. 

Seed is the beginning of life. It is suspended life force energy. A seed is full of life potential and when fully expressed gives rise to the future. Seed heritage is deeply bound in our cultural traditions. Seed is our tether to the past, to mother, to our ancestry, it is also the promise of the future. 

Our ability to grow, eat and sustain life is a basic human need. When people are displaced, and land is destroyed, so is culture. 

One thing about plants is that when they don’t have all that they need to thrive, they focus their energy on resilience and survival. They can rise up in the most nutrient and resource deficient areas and still make a way. We find the most resilient and self-determined of weeds make their way through the cracks in concrete.... that’s called uprising. 

Plants are like people, people are like plants. When we lack the resources and emotional nutrients needed to thrive, we focus on survival and lean into our resilience to carry us through while being marred by trauma. 
We rise up through the cracks we’ve fallen into. 

Plant seeds of change. Plant seeds of consciousness. We all deserve to be seen, to be heard, to have dignity and to belong. We all deserve water, clean air, sunlight, adequate shelter and culturally appropriate food stuffs. We all deserve to be free: free of occupation, free of state sanctioned violence, free of terror. Our Palestinian siblings have a right to live fully expressed lives. 

Learn more about @vivien.sansour and the seed-saving she is doing, in honor of her homeland. 🙏🏽

node.title: This Palestinian Woman is Fighting for Food Justice by Saving Heirloom Seed

#ad BEDITATIONS - Quality sleep is the foundation of a healthy mind, body and spirit.

Sleep helps boost immunity, improves our mood and assists in recovery. Feelings of stress or anxiety can prevent us from achieving quality rest that we need for optimal wellbeing. Meditation helps to relax the nervous system and calm the body to help us fall asleep and stay asleep. 

What you sleep on also matters.SleepIQ technology in my @sleepnumber 360 smart bed helps me see and feel the difference in my sleep quality. Each month I get a wellness report that analyzes my sleep trends and helps me see how the things I do during the day affect my sleep – whether it be an intense workout or a calming meditation before bed. 

This BEDITATION practice is meditation while lying in bed. All you need is a comfortable surface to lie down, set the tone for your experience by softening the lighting or drawing the curtains, prop yourself up so you are cozy and focus on your breathing. When you engage in this practice you may notice some differences in how grounded you feel in your daily life. It’s my intention that you cultivate a deeper understanding of the physical body and how to best nurture yourself to support our personal growth. This is a moment for us to create space for ourselves to have an experience of ultimate rest. 

Getting better quality sleep is truly life-changing and I want that for each and every one of you! What’s the single most important thing you can do to start each day with more energy, optimism, and ultimate freedom? Diet and exercise? Better time management? Sheer determination? For me the answer is clear: Reclaiming deep and truly restorative rest. #SmarterSleep

My Soul Cries for You every second Ra Ra. You belong in our arms. 

You belong with us. Mission. Purpose. Vision. Clear. 

We are always connected no matter the distance. You are always with us my precious baby. 

Mama and Baba Love You. 

If you are new to this page our Sun was “Legally Kidnapped”. It’s been 114 days without Our SUNshine. 

Our sun was unrightfully taken from us due to a false medical report by Child Abuse Pediatrician, Sally Smith who works at Johns Hopkins All Children’s Hospital, in St.Petersburg, FL and CPI Officer Danielle McCoy of Manatee County Sheriff’s Department. 

They claim we refused a medically necessary B12 shot for our sun, which we didn’t. They banned us permanently from the hospital forcing us to leave our sun alone with strangers and then placed him in a foster home with a white family, bypassing all of our qualified relatives. 

Ra had just weaned from my breast while at the hospital and had never been without his mama and baba. EVER. The trauma that they have caused can never be undone. The trauma from all the nights Ra lay in that hospital crib crying out for his mama can NEVER be reversed. 

Ra is our entire world and now everyday we have to relive the beyond heart ache of how they tore our beautiful family apart. They have caused unnecessary trauma to our child… our family and Must be held accountable! 

Please click the link in our bio to Read our Story, watch our highlights and IGTV for more info. and Donate to our #BringRaHome Campaign. 

We appreciate your support in standing with us as we use our voices to bring justice for our Sun, our family, and other families torn apart to such a corrupt and broken system.

Mama Glow Webinar: 
Navigating Infant Feeding
Presented by: @bobbie 
 WEDNESDAY, AUGUST 18th, 6:30pm ET via Zoom - Register today!
 
In the month of August, we observe Breastfeeding Awareness Month. We also acknowledge that there are many paths to feeding a newborn. We recognize the challenges and triumphs of the infant feeding journey and support parents as they feed their littles ones the best way they know how.

Join us for a lively and informative webinar where we will explore feeding on multiple levels. Whether you breastfeed/ chest-feed/ body feed, bottle feed, supplement or formula feed, we are here to help answer your questions in a judge-free zone.

This Webinar is Presented by: Bobbie

Meet the Panelists:

SADA K.
Singer, Writer, & Mother
Sada K. has expanded her brand to a lifestyle brand connecting with her following through music, media, womanhood, family, wellness, and inspiration.
IG: @sadakmusic 

Amna Husain, MD, IBCLC
Pediatrician and Lactation Consultant
Dr. Husain is a board-certified pediatrician, board certified lactation consultant, Her pediatric philosophy inspired her to create her own concierge pediatric practice.
IG: @dr.amnahusain
 
Dairian Roberts (she/her)occupational therapist (OTR/L) and international board certified lactation consultant (IBCLC)
Dairian is a Los Angeles based occupational therapist (OT) and international board certified lactation consultant (IBCLC). She supports families throughout their infant feeding journey from the first latch to first food, and anything else in between.
IG: @humbledbymotherhood

Kim Chappell
VP of Marketing for Bobbie
Kim is a mama of two with a third on the way living in San Francisco, CA. She is passionate about supporting all modern parents in their feeding journey from breastmilk to formula and shaking the stigmas surrounding how we choose to feed our babies.
IG: @kimchappy
 
The conversation will be moderated by Mama Glow Founder, Latham Thomas 

We look forward to you joining us Wednesday! Tag a friend! 

And if you miss it, it will be recorded

Glow Moment - Hey people. I have been offline for a few weeks. Just getting back here to share a few things and will be coming back more consistently in the fall. 

I wanted to share a beautiful conversation with one of my favorite people @gottesss who is a witch, a spiritual sorceress, a tarot genius and moon maven. I spent time with her on her Moonbeaming podcast. 

We talked about liminality, birth and rites of passage. Liminal comes from Latin, meaning “threshold” when we enter into a liminal space we have separated from our normal life and social roles to dissolve and transform and move into another phase of our lives. This is a deeply spiritual and emotional time of passage and requires support. 

Rites of passage and birthing rites are sacred. And we are designed to experience safety, dignity, belonging and transcendence - it’s part of our genetic blueprint. 

So the role of a doula or birth worker is not just to be a presence of support, but to bear witness and protect a spiritual transformation that is unfolding. We are here to protect the sanctity of the birth experience, regardless of outcome. 

Birthing people are meant to come on the other side of the experience and feel empowered and bring something with them that they didn’t have when they started, and they leave parts of themselves behind to emerge transformed. What each person carries with them is different, but it’s their own medicine, their own magic. 

Tune in to Moonbeaming with host @gottesss ❤️ wherever you listen to podcasts. 

#birth #sacred #primal #doula #ritesofpassage #liminalspace #spirituality #selfcare

Glow Moment - Birth is sacred. The birthing ritual provides a space for us to slow dance with God. To tap into our ancestral wisdom and Sankofa, to reach back into our lineage and retrieve what we need to continue this divine path forward. 

I’ve known this special lady nearly two decades. We met at prenatal yoga class when we were pregnant 19 years ago with our Cancer 🦀 babies who were born days apart. We both delivered with midwives at Elizabeth Seton Childbearing Center- the only free-standing birth center in NYC. 

We have been through a lot together and have always been there for one another. We are both Taurus mamas with similar idiosyncrasies and moods. She’s an incredible mother, wife, sister, daughter and friend. 

While we are both preparing to send our Cubs out into the world as they start college in a few short weeks, she just welcomed a newborn son. He came a day after her daughter Kennedy turned 18. God bless. 🙏🏽

I want to lift up and affirm, safe, dignified, healthy, affordable, patient centric and supportive birth for all Black birthing people. Especially in a culture that does not value Black life. We can do this. It is your birth rite to be witnessed and supported by the people you love. Birth is communal. We evolved for support during this process. Curate your desired birth team, including those who are living and those who have passed on. Reach back for that ancestral guidance. You can do this. 

I’m super proud of you Travoya. Love you long time queen. Please stop the campaign to get me to have another baby… that ship has docked, hasn’t sailed yet… I’m thinking about it - but that’s as far as it’s going. ❤️❤️❤️ 

#babyfever #glowmoment #mamaglow #friendship #motherhood #birth #sacred

✨GLOWING LIVE WITH LATHAM ✨ IG LIVE series on @iamwellandgood 
_
Hey family! New guest alert 🚨For my interview series in partnership with WELL+GOOD. I interview incredible BIPOC healers and entrepreneurs who are forging a path of service in their communities. TODAY, July 22, as we head into Olympic season, I will be going live with @sanyarichiross - Olympic gold medalist (track and field), mama and founder of the @mommination community. She is also the host of the @nikewomen new visual podcast series, ULTRA SOUND - Conversations for Black Birthing People. 
_
Sanya Richards-Ross is a Jamaican-American former track and field athlete who competed internationally for the United States. At the 2012 Summer Olympics, she won gold in the 400 metres after finishing third at the 2008 Summer Olympics. Richards-Ross has also won Olympic gold in the 4×400 meters relay at the 2004 Summer Olympics, the 2008 Summer Olympics, and the 2012 Summer Olympics. She was the best 400m runner in the world for a decade, ranking No. 1 in the world from 2005-2009 and again in 2012. 
_
We know that there is so much wisdom within our communities and I can’t wait for you to hear from Sanya and some of the other amazing wellness leaders and personalities we have lined up. 
_
Join @glowmaven, doula, wellness maven, and author of Own Your Glow, as she speaks with luminaries from across the wellness industry who are working to create change and promote healing for their communities. These soulful live discussions will give you a peek into their personal self-care routines and rituals while also shining a light on the health disparities that prevent many people from living their most well and fully expressed lives. 
_
See you at 1pm ET today on @iamwellandgood ! #glowinglivewithlatham #iamwellandgood

The Black Maternal Health Crisis has taught us that education, self-advocacy and a birth team are important tools for an empowered birth. Certified Professional Midwife (CPM), Licensed Midwife (LM), GrandMidwife Apprentice (19yrs), Registered & Certified Sangoma (South African Traditional Healer)

My baby boy is officially grown now y’all. Born at 1:09pm on July 13th, 2003 on the full moon and double rainbow 🌈 what a blessing and honor it’s been to raise such a special human being. 

We’ve had 18 beautiful summers together and in a few short weeks I will take him to Berklee School of Music where he will begin his freshman year of college in music school. 

I’m feeling so many emotions. The fact that Papa Rick (his grandpa) made his way to the afterlife just at the precipice of Fulano crossing the threshold into adulthood isn’t lost on me. As an ancestor now, I know that he will be a constant presence guiding Fulano into the next phase of his life. I know that Fulano will carry all of the lessons we have poured into him. I know he will carve his own path forward and I’ll be here watching and cheering. 

I’m just here taking deep breaths and leaning on my support system. I’m thankful to all of you who have sent blessings to our family. I am thankful to all of our village keepers who have been part of Fuli’s life, helping me and Nemo raise him. 

My darling Fuli, I’m so proud of who you are and who you are becoming. May God continue to flank you with blessings and cover you. Happy birthday beloved baby boy. You’re on your way.

Glow Moment - This is me & Papa the day before he transitioned. He still had so much strength & was squeezing my hand with all he had left. Papa is Nemo’s dad, my son’s paternal grandfather, he was my father-in-law & he is my forever heavenly bonus father. He came into my life 2 decades ago, was there when I went into labor and gave birth to Fulano & has been there ever since. Papa was part of my birth village and a caretaker for my son. He was the one person I could always rely upon. I was able to advance my career as a doula because when I was on call, Papa was on call too and would welcome my son in the middle of the night and take care of him when I was headed to a birth. 

He supported my artistic expression, encouraged me to continue painting, drawing, bookmaking & printmaking. We spent days in the MET where he would unleash his infinite knowledge about art and walk us through the Egyptian hall and make our way to the School of Paris. He built an art collection for my son since birth. Fulano would spend several weeks in the summer months upstate where he would paint massive canvasses alongside his grandfather. They were best friends and theirs was a beautiful relationship to witness. 

Over the years this man of great strength began to slow down and was impacted by illness. As Papa’s time horizon began to shrink and we knew we would have just a few months with him, Fulano and the grand daughters were with him every day. 

The day before he passed 3 of us gave him a ritual bath, changed his sheets and bedding, washed and combed his hair, put his cologne on him, moisturized his lips, he looked dignified. He never wanted to be a burden to others. It was an honor to anoint him and take care of him when he couldn’t take care of himself. 

While I stroked his forehead, he gazed at me and said faintly “goodnight honey” those were his last words to me… words that he always uttered when we would say our farewells. He hadn’t really spoken all day, but this time it felt final. I knew that would be the last time our eyes met. I knew that was the last time I would kiss him goodnight. That was the last moment I shared with Papa before he went home to glory. 🙏🏽
